The key insight is that in the initial state, an agent only knows their own secret. For `n ≥ 2`, if no calls are made, no agent can be an expert since they don't know others' secrets.

```lean
/-- Among n agents, to make k an expert, we need at least n-1 calls. -/
lemma exp_needs_n_min_one_calls (S : List (Call n))
    (h : isExpert (after S) k)
    : n - 1 < S.length := by
  cases n with
  | zero => exact Fin.elim0 k
  | succ m =>
    cases m with
    | zero =>
      simp only [Nat.succ_sub_succ_eq_sub, Nat.sub_zero, Nat.zero_lt_succ]
    | succ m' =>
      simp only [Nat.succ_sub_succ_eq_sub, Nat.sub_zero]
      by_contra hc
      push_neg at hc
      have hne : (⟨0, Nat.zero_lt_succ _⟩ : Fin (m' + 2)) ≠ ⟨1, Nat.one_lt_succ_succ m'⟩ := by
        intro heq
        exact absurd (congrArg Fin.val heq) (by omega)
      cases S with
      | nil =>
        unfold isExpert after makeCalls at h
        simp only [List.foldl_nil] at h
        have h0 := h ⟨0, Nat.zero_lt_succ _⟩
        have h1 := h ⟨1, Nat.one_lt_succ_succ m'⟩
        simp only [initialState] at h0 h1
        exact absurd (h0.symm.trans h1) hne
      | cons c cs =>
        simp only [List.length_cons] at hc
        omega
```
